  <p>
    No amount of money replaces a person. We won't pretend otherwise. But when someone's negligence takes a family member from you, Arizona law provides a path to hold them accountable. That accountability matters. It covers the financial devastation a death causes. It forces the responsible parties to answer for their actions. And it can prevent the same negligence from hurting another family.
  </p>

  <h2>Arizona's Wrongful Death Statute</h2>

  <p>
    Arizona wrongful death claims are governed by ARS 12-611 through 12-613. These statutes define who can file, what damages are available, and how claims proceed. Understanding the specifics matters because wrongful death law varies significantly from state to state.
  </p>

  <p>
    Under ARS 12-612, the right to file belongs to the surviving spouse, children, parents, or guardian of the deceased. The personal representative of the estate can also bring the claim. If multiple family members have standing, they typically file together so the court can allocate damages appropriately.
  </p>

  <h2>The Two-Year Clock</h2>

  <p>
    Arizona gives surviving families two years from the date of death to file a wrongful death lawsuit. That deadline is strict. Courts rarely grant exceptions.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two years may sound generous, but these cases require significant investigation. Medical records, accident reconstruction, expert analysis, and witness depositions all take time. If the death involved a government entity, such as a crash on a state highway or negligence at a public facility, the notice of claim deadline under ARS 12-821.01 is just 180 days.
  </p>

  <h2>What Families Can Recover</h2>

  <p>
    Arizona's wrongful death statute allows compensation for both economic and non-economic losses. Economic damages include the deceased person's lost income and future earning capacity, medical expenses incurred before death, and funeral and burial costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Non-economic damages cover the loss of love, companionship, and guidance. For surviving spouses, that includes the loss of consortium. For children, it includes the loss of parental guidance and support during their development. These damages are real, substantial, and recognized by Arizona courts.
  </p>

  <p>
    A separate survival action can recover damages for the pain and suffering the deceased experienced between the injury and death. Both claims can proceed simultaneously.
  </p>

  <h2>Common Causes of Wrongful Death in Arizona</h2>

  <p>
    Car and truck crashes are the most common cause of wrongful death claims in Arizona. But these cases arise from many situations: medical malpractice, workplace accidents, defective products, nursing home neglect, pedestrian crashes, and criminal acts.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each cause requires a different investigation and different evidence. A medical malpractice wrongful death case needs expert testimony about the standard of care. A trucking case needs FMCSA records and electronic logging data. We tailor our approach to the facts of your case.
  </p>

  <h2>Why These Cases Require Experienced Attorneys</h2>

  <p>
    Wrongful death cases involve high stakes for everyone. Insurance companies assign their most experienced adjusters and defense attorneys. They'll challenge liability, dispute damages, and use every procedural tool available to minimize their exposure.
  </p>

  <p>
    You need attorneys who've handled these cases before. Attorneys who know how to investigate, who understand the damages model, and who can stand in front of a jury if necessary. We prepare every wrongful death case for trial. That preparation is what drives fair settlements.
  </p>

